    <p><font size='3' color='#000000' face='Arial'><small>The metals which can be used as far
    as we are currently aware are: <strong>Silver</strong>, <strong>Electrum</strong>, <strong>Gold</strong>,
    and <strong>Platinum</strong>.&nbsp; Jewellery made with this material will raise your
    skill regardless of whether it is enchanted or not. However, it will not provide any
    magical benefits unless the metal has been enchanted. There is no difference in skill gain
    or difficulty when working with an enchanted metal as compared with its normal state.
    &nbsp; Metal can only be enchanted by an enchanter, although there are items which can do
    some lower level metal enchantments.&nbsp; The enchantment spells are located in the
    darkness of the Library of Neriak.</small></font></p>
    <p><font size='3' color='#000000' face='Arial'><small>The difference between gems is not
    just the price of them.&nbsp; Lower class jewels generally provide half the benefit in
    jewellery than the upper ones.&nbsp; The Rare ones provide the greatest benefits, but are
    disgustingly expensive since they only come off high level NPC's and must be bought or
    traded for.&nbsp; Diamond, Jacinth, Fire Opal, and Black Sapphire currently encompass
    these, although there may be more that we are not yet aware of.</small></font></p>
    <p><font size='3' color='#0e024d' face='Arial'><strong>Increasing Your Skill</strong></font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial'><small>There are two approaches to raising skill depending on when
    you start.&nbsp; If you start early without much money you will want to max your skill to
    21 at the guild with practise points.&nbsp; After this you have to make items to raise
    skill.&nbsp; </small><br>
    <br>
    <small>If on the other hand you have some money already, you may want the minimum 1 skill
    to begin your trade, and save practise points for later in life.</small></font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial'><small>Once you are ready to make items, start with the lowest cost
    item and work up to increase your skill. You will want to have high wisdom, intelligence
    and carisma when doing this.&nbsp; Use your tiems, jewellery, and spells to maximum effect
    here.&nbsp; Wisdom will reduce failures, although even with high wisdom, skill is still
    the determining factor, particularly on platinum and rare gem objects.&nbsp; Intelligence
    will help to advance your skill faster.&nbsp; The maximum skill however is 200 and you
    will notice quite a bit of slow down from 180 onwards.&nbsp; High int will however help
    alot during the Silver and Electrum phase of your career.&nbsp; Charisma will reduce costs
    of components and increase yout sale price back to the vendors.&nbsp; When training in
    skill most jewellers do not bother with enchanting the metal they are working with. &nbsp;
    They buy the bars make items, sell them back to the vendor at a loss, and buy more
    materials until they are broke.&nbsp; Higher charisma helps to get you an extra few bars
    and gems, which could just be a couple more skill points.</small></font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial'><small>Once an item becomes trivial you will no longer gain skill
    working with that gem and metal and should move on to the next one.&nbsp; You can refer to
    our <a href='jewel_trivials.asp'><strong>trivial
    chart</strong></a> to determine when you should move on.</small></font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial'><small>There are a number of different <a href='jewel_locs.asp'><strong>vendors</strong></a>
    all over Norrath to help supply you your materials.&nbsp; Some can only be found off NPC's
    though, and these are normally the most valuable.&nbsp; In determining what items can be
    made you can also refer to our <a href='jewel_table.asp'><strong>Jewllery
    Table</strong></a>.</small></font></p>
    <p>&nbsp;</p>
    <p><font size='3' color='#0e024d' face='Arial'><strong>Transcript of The Legacy of
    Jewelcraft</strong></font></p>
    <p><font size='2' face='Arial'>This technique is the legacy of jewelcraft Master Srettib,
    who was able to draw upon the force of mineral essence. His passion for working with the
    rarest and most beautiful stones quickly lead him to concoct a firm setting to ensure the
    precious stones would not be lost (as was often the case with previous wire techniques).
    His artistic genius not only lead him to create molding settings, bu enabled him to
    convoke the latent magical powers within stones and externalize them. He coupled stones
    with various metals to control the outcome of the powers he unleashed.</font></p>
    <p><font size='2' face='Arial'>Every jewelcrafter learns Srettib's techiques, and in
    homage to his memory, all other forms of jewelcraft have been abandoned.</font></p>
    <p><font size='2' face='Arial'><em>Jewelcraft Master Srettib's Instructions:</em></font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial'><font size='2'>All jewllery carries a unique charm. Exquisite stones
    placed in the finest crafted settings, and more likely to release the force of mineral
    essence.&nbsp; Try various combinations.&nbsp; Combine any stone with any metal to create
    unique jewllery. Precious stones are generally cut so that they will reflect the most
    light. Other stones may be tumbled for a smooth surface or left untumbled if they have an
    interesting shape. Pearls and crystals are generally left natural.&nbsp; Use the molds in
    your jewellery kit and pour melted metal into the mold, allow it to cool and remove the
    metal from the mold.&nbsp; To add cut stones, carve a pronged cup mold so that the prongs
    are down and the base of the cup is at the top.&nbsp; Weld the base of the cup to the top
    of the ring, bracelet, etc. Insert the stone into the cup and carefully bend down the
    prongs to trap the stone.&nbsp; To add odd shaped untumbled stones, custom carve a mold to
    fit the stone with bottom of the cup at the bottom of the mold. Pour a small amount of
    melted metal into the mold and immediately insert the stone. Allow to cool and remove from
    the mold.</font> </font></p>
